TY  - JOUR
AU  - Garlappi, Lorenzo
AU  - Shu, Tao
AU  - Yan, Hong
T1  - Default Risk, Shareholder Advantage, and Stock Returns
PY  - 2008
Y1  - 2008/11/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhl044
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 21
IS  - 6
SP  - 2743
EP  - 2778
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - This paper examines the relationship between default probability and stock returns. Using the Expected Default Frequency (EDF) of Moody's KMV, we document that higher default probabilities are not associated with higher expected stock returns. Within a model of bargaining between equity holders and debt holders in default, we show that the relationship between default probability and equity return is (i) upward sloping for firms where shareholders can extract little benefit from renegotiation (low “shareholder advantage”) and (ii) humped and downward sloping for firms with high shareholder advantage. This dichotomy implies that distressed firms with stronger shareholder advantage should exhibit lower expected returns in the cross section. Our empirical evidence, based on several proxies for shareholder advantage, is consistent with the model's predictions.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhl044
ER  - 



